    <id>2</id>
    <title>Combined summary - Post-Quantum BIP-86 Recovery via zk-STARK Proof of BIP-32 Seed Knowledge</title>
    <updated>2026-05-25T06:20:27.899446+00:00</updated>
    <link href="https://gnusha.org/pi/bitcoindev/49236a10-94ea-440a-9b53-63ae2c7ac964n@googlegroups.com/T/#mfd62c037275b32e57e002a27821e4473f3c03605" rel="alternate"/>
    <published>2026-04-08 03:39:00+00:00</published>
    <summary>The recent discussion on the Bitcoin Development Mailing List has highlighted significant advancements in zk-STARK proofs and their integration with blockchain technologies, specifically focusing on providing quantum-resistant security measures for Bitcoin transactions. The dialogue was initiated by Olaoluwa Osuntokun, who revisited a side project aiming to extend TinyGo to produce RISC-V ELF binaries that function within the risc0 platform, facilitating the generation of zk-STARK proofs for arbitrary programs. This project is particularly aimed at constructing proofs that a Taproot output public key was generated using BIP-32 through a BIP-86 derivation path.
Osuntokun's initiative addresses potential future scenarios where quantum computing capabilities could compromise traditional cryptographic methods. By utilizing zk-STARKs, which rely solely on symmetric cryptography, there's an inherent post-quantum security assumed, making it a robust alternative against quantum attacks. The proposed system integrates various components including modifications to TinyGo for RISC-V support, enhancements to the risc0 repository, and new utilities in the Go programming environment to manage and verify these proofs efficiently.
Further elaborations by other contributors, such as 'conduition', suggest optimizations and alternatives to simplify the circuit or guest program involved in generating these proofs. For instance, reducing the computational steps required for proving knowledge of a secret key by focusing only on necessary elements like hardened derivation steps, which could significantly decrease proof size and improve performance.
Moreover, discussions extend into future applications and modifications, such as batch and incremental proof aggregations discussed by Osuntokun in later correspondences. These would allow untrusted parties to compile multiple proofs into a single compact proof, potentially conserving blockchain space significantly. This method leverages a recursive approach to ensure that regardless of the number of proofs aggregated, the final proof size remains constant.
The discourse also covers broader implications for Bitcoin’s protocol, contemplating a possible soft fork that could disable the keyspend path of Taproot outputs, compelling spends to go through the script path. Such a change would align with the quantum-resistant properties of zk-STARKs, preserving the integrity and security of the blockchain against advancing quantum threats.
Overall, the contributions reflect a proactive approach to blockchain security, considering both immediate enhancements via zk-STARK proofs for existing cryptographic mechanisms and long-term strategies to safeguard against quantum computing disruptions. These discussions are pivotal in shaping the future resilience of Bitcoin and similar cryptocurrencies, ensuring they remain secure as technological landscapes evolve.</summary>
